SIMPLE: invocation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Invocation
<hw>In`vo*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>invocation</ets>, L. <ets>invocatio</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or form of calling for the assistance or
presence of some superior being; earnest and solemn entreaty; esp.,
prayer offered to a divine being.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sweet <qex>invocation</qex> of a child; most pretty and
pathetical!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The whole poem is a prayer to Fortune, and the
<qex>invocation</qex> is divided between the two deities.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A call or summons; especially, a
judicial call, demand, or order; <as>as, the <ex>invocation</ex> of
papers or evidence into court</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invocatory</ent>⟦br⟧
